title: For Sale/Trade:  (SOLD) S&W 1076 complete package (SOLD)
postcontent:
S&W 1076 civilian version (with magazine safety). THE 10mm pistol! A whacking chunk of American Stainless steel. Accurate, with power to boot. Barrel/barrel bushing are lapped. Trigger was fixed by S&W back in the early 90s. Six S&W magazines. One CrossBreed Supertuck holster, custom leather pancake holster. Hand fitted rubber Hogue grips (have the original "derlin" grips, too). Adjustable LPA rear sight. I also have the original Novaks. Box and papers. Reloading dies, brass, and loads of ammunition (which will cost extra). This is a complete set-up.

This was the pistol that was designed for the FBI following the findings of the Miami-Shootout disaster. The 10mm is the father of the 40 S&W and .357 SIG and more powerful than both. It uses widely available 40 caliber bullets. 10mm has more energy at 100 yards than a 45 ACP does at the muzzle.

This pistol has not been made for nearly two decades and it looks as if no more Full-Size 3rd Generation S&Ws will be made. This was their king. It has the SIG type frame-mounted de-cocker, regarded by many as superior to the difficult S&W type slide-safety. The double action trigger on this pistol is remarkably smooth, and single action is very good. 

If you have not experienced 10mm, I suggest you do. It is makes the 40 Short and Weak and 45 ACP feel like a joke. Unlike the Glock 20, the 1076 is truly up the the task of handling full-house 10mm, not simply the FBI-lite.

Unlike some FBI and Kentucky State police trade-ins, this has not been abused. It is in superior condition.

Ohio DL absolutely required. Ohio CCW holders and Miami Rifle and Pistol club members given preference.

title: For Sale:  Remingtom 1903 A3 All original WW2
postcontent:
For sale is a Model 1903 A3. This is a great all original WW11 rifle and an excellent shooter. This is a very rare model of 1903A3's, that have some characteristics of the older 1903 model 1919 (flip-up ladder style rear sight and no finger groove on the stock) very very cool old design.

About the rifle (serial number and reference book used to get history of THIS SPECIFIC rifle!):
It was manufactured in November of 1942 at the Remington typewriter factory in New York, New York. It was shipped out to the Marine Corps that month for use in New guniea and the Solomons. From there it traveled from island to island, hopping with the Marines through Guadalcanal, Tarawa, Guam, Tinian, Saipan, and Peleliu, seeing action on every one. Before Iwo Jima, they were replaced entirely by the M1 Carbine, except for a few in commando missions (not this one though). This rifle was then shipped back to the states for use in boot camp as marksmanship training rifle from 1944 to the end of the war. Then used as a drill rifle by all services. (from the fleck of white paint left on the stock, and the overall condition, my guess is that it was used by military police in Korea, not as a drill rifle.) That is up until 1955-56, where all M1903 rifles were re-collected, refurbished if necessary, re-parkerized if necessary, and then sold to retired WWII and Korean war vets as hunting rifles for $25.50. Officers were allowed to hand-pick their rifles and that is were the majority of collector grade rifles came from. Some were converted to hunting rifles with new stocks and are now worth around $200. The untouched military versions can be worth thousands. The rest were sent out to VFW, ROTC, and other military units as ceremonial drill rifles where their barrels were filled with lead and receivers were rendered inoperable or were used in military burials. This one sat unfired in a cabinet for the last 55 years completely untouched. I've only put 40 rounds through it.

Asking $950 obo. I may be open to trades, let me know what you have.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Walther P-22 Mini Eagle!!!!!
location: Coventry,Rhode Island, New York, United States
postcontent:
The action of the Walther P22 is standard double action/single action with a 11/4 lb trigger pull. If you want to shoot the gun double action, the decocker is really odd on this gun. To decock it, you set the safety on safe and pull the trigger. Yep, that's not a misprint...you pull the trigger to safely drop the hammer. The best route is to not bother with double action shooting with this gun. The single action shooting is easy and fun.The Walther P22 comes in two sizes: one with a 5" barrel (mine shown) which also has a compensator that probably doesn't actually accomplish anything. It just makes the gun look cooler. It also comes in a model with a 3.4 " barrel with no compensator.

The gun features interchangeable backstraps to better fit a shooters hand, ambidextrous controls, magazine disconnect, hammer safety and firing pin safety, fixed (read more accurate) barrel, and interchangeable barrel. The gun is only 18.7 oz, comes with two 10 round magazines, rear sight adjustable for windage, 3 interchangeable front sights for elevation, sights of the 3 dot configuration.The gun is plenty accurate with the fixed barrel contributing to that aspect of the gun. With it being super light, it is easy to maneuver and the sights come in line quickly on the 5" model. People who shot it initially loved it and could hit anything they shot at with little time to get used to the gun.
When I purchased the Walther P22, I thought it to be a little pricey at around $360 plus tax new. But considering the weight and size, ability of people of all sizes to shoot it, accuracy, and exceptional dependability, I now consider it to be a good value. I would highly recommend it to anyone looking for an acceptable .22 pistol for the whole family.

All paperwork and tools+hardware+2 mags original case and secondary stylish case included.
Pictures available upon request please contact me Via e-mail.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Great Condition H&K P7 Package!
postcontent:
I have for sale or trade a rare and unique Heckler and Koch P-7 PSP. These guns are very rare and highly unique. This specific one was made in West Germany in June of 1987. It is in great condition with very minor holster wear on the slide near the muzzle and the rear sights.

These guns are no longer produced and have high value. The P7 is a semi-automatic, blowback-operated firearm. It features a unique gas-delayed blow-back locking system, which reduces felt recoil and makes for reliable operation. Even if the extractor would break, it would still eject casings.

It also uses a squeeze cocking lever in the frame. Making this on of the, if not the safest handgun, without that squeeze cocker being held, the striker is not cocked, and it will not fire. The squeeze cocker also is used as the slide release after changing mages, making it a quick single action to fire after loading a new magazine. This also encourages tight grip increasing reliability.

Another unique feature is its barrel which is fixed into the frame. This serves to greatly improve accuracy, the barrel does not move when a round is discharged or move if the slide is in movement. This also helps bring the center of mass move towards the hand, reducing felt recoil.

These truly are great guns. I am quite surprised no one has tried to make one similar to it recently. I absolutely hate to sell it but I am looking for a more CCW friendly handgun.


Comes with:
-Original Box
-Original Manual
-Original Cleaning Rod
-2 Magazines (8 round H&K mags)(Mags can go for $60 each)
-Leather Belt Holster (Hard to find)

Looking to sell for $675.00. I may negotiate on this price, give me an offer. Don't waste my time with insulting offers.


I will respond to emails quickly. Any questions about the gun, please feel free to ask.

postcontent:
I have available a PAIR of custom built long range hunting/target rifles. One is left handed, the other right. These rifles are identical in all respects except for one being left handed, so all details listed below are the same for each.

-Built on Savage Long Action with Accu-Trigger
-Wood laminate thumb hole stock
-Chambered in 6.5 Creedmoor
-26" Stainless Match barrel by Criterion, varmint contour
-Precision ground recoil lug
-Action is pillar and glass bedded
-Free floated barrel
-Barrels are broken in, with long range hunting load development complete
-Scope is Leupold VX-3 4.5-14x40 CDS (Coupon for free custom turret included)
-Burris Signature Zee rings

Both rifles have fired groups at 1/4MOA at 100 yards and have held less than 1/2MOA out to 500 yards. Leupold CDS scopes have exposed elevation turret for easy range adjustment. Scopes come with coupon for free custom turret built by Leupold for load and chosen environment. Loads developed using 140gr Berger VLD hunting bullet, scopes are zeroed and data will be included for range adjustment. 20 hand loaded cartridges included with each rifle. One set of reloading dies, brass, and left over bullets can be added with either rifle.

We have found these to be very light recoiling, pleasant shooters with fantastic long range accuracy in the right hands. Though these would make excellent target rifles, they were built with long range hunting in mind, and one rifle was used to take large buck two weeks ago at 480 yards with a cross wind. Single shot to vitals, took 10 slow steps then fell over dead.

Asking $1650 each, $3000 gets the pair. Willing to discuss selling without optic if you already have one.

Feel free with any questions. Thanks for looking!

Up for quick sale is a beautiful Bushmaster. It features a 20" HBAR barrel, and is unbelievably accurate. The CAA Stock is awesome, and lets you customize it for a perfect fit and cheekweld. The stock alone goes for $200+. I am in Canton and will make a bit of a drive if needed. If the buyer would like to test fire it to verify accuracy and function that could be arranged. H1 Buffer
Original Stock

Hard Shell Case
